      "question": "If the polynomial $p(x) = x^4 - 2x^3 + 3x^2 - ax + b$ is exactly divisible by the polynomial $g(x) = x^2 - 2x + 1$, then the values of $a$ and $b$ are respectively:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "The divisor $g(x) = x^2 - 2x + 1$ can be factored as $(x - 1)^2$.",
          "For $p(x)$ to be exactly divisible by $(x - 1)^2$, $x = 1$ must be a zero of $p(x)$ and $p'(x)$.",
          "Setting $p(1) = 0$, we get $1 - 2 + 3 - a + b = 0$, which simplifies to $-a + b = -2$, or $b - a = -2$.",
          "Differentiating $p(x)$, we get $p'(x) = 4x^3 - 6x^2 + 6x - a$.",
          "Setting $p'(1) = 0$, we get $4 - 6 + 6 - a = 0$, which gives $a = 4$.",
          "Substituting $a = 4$ into $b - a = -2$, we get $b - 4 = -2$, so $b = 2$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$g(x) = (x-1)^2 \\Rightarrow x=1 \\text{ is a double root of } p(x) \\\\ p(1) = 1^4 - 2(1)^3 + 3(1)^2 - a(1) + b = 0 \\\\ 1 - 2 + 3 - a + b = 0 \\Rightarrow b - a = -2 \\\\ p'(x) = 4x^3 - 6x^2 + 6x - a \\\\ p'(1) = 4(1)^3 - 6(1)^2 + 6(1) - a = 0 \\\\ 4 - 6 + 6 - a = 0 \\Rightarrow a = 4 \\\\ b - 4 = -2 \\Rightarrow b = 2$"
      },
